Executive Summary

The project team has analysed and developed predictive analysis models for a dataset provided by Petrfinder.my (Malaysias largest online database for rehoming household pets). We shall develop models using clustering, classification and regression approaches. Our overall objective is to provide data insights and offer business advice for the application of our models.


Introduction

The dataset will shall analyse comes from PetFinder.my website. Set up since 2008, they have over 150,000 on their database and lead the way in animal welfare in Malaysia, helping pets get adopted to loving homes.

PetFinder exists in several countries, but is very important in Malaysia where pets are common but strays are increasing. Here are some interesting facts.

  • Almost 60% of homes in Malaysia have pets, 20% are dog owners;
  • Stray animals in Malaysia are on the rise; and
  • In 2021, there was an increase of almost 300% in pet abandonment.

2. Data pre-processing

Before we begin our deeper analysis and development of models, we must first look closely at the dataset and perform any necessary pre-processing.

2.1 Type of animal

There are a total of 14,993 observations in the data dataset, consisting of only dogs and cats. We can reasonably expect there to be an inherent difference between the species, and for this reason we have chosen to look specifically at dogs.

2.2 AdoptionSpeed

The data has an AdoptionSpeed for each dog, ranging from 0 (adopted on the same day as posting) to 4 (not adopted), as per below.

0 - Pet was adopted on the same day as it was listed.
1 - Pet was adopted between 1 and 7 days (1st week) after being listed.
2 - Pet was adopted between 8 and 30 days (1st month) after being listed.
3 - Pet was adopted between 31 and 90 days (2nd & 3rd month) after being listed.
4 - No adoption after 100 days of being listed. (There are no pets in this dataset that waited between 90 and 100 days).

AdoptionSpeed n
0 170
1 1435
2 2164
3 1949
4 2414

We consider it more important than the speed, was whether the dog was adopted or not. We have therefore decided to create a new variable (binary Yes/No) as per below. We will later remove variable AdoptionSpeed from the dataset.

Comment: We will later remove variable AdoptionSpeed from the dataset.

Our analysis revealed a very high proportion of dogs as Breed 307 (mixed breed) and smaller numbers of purebred/known breeds. We have therefore decided to add a new variable, simply denoting whether the dog is a purebred (or known breed) or mixed (or unknown).

3.0 Clustering: Age of pets

We shall now explore the age of pets in more detail, and use clustering to develop a new variable in the dataset.

Please note, the age listed for each pet represents the age in months at the date of listing.

3.1 Exploration of Age data

The distribution of age over our dataset is positively skewed where the mean is higher than the median. The average age variable in our dataset is 12.91 months, while this median age is 3. This is consistent with unwanted young animals being abandoned, as the median shows us that 50 % of animals put up for adoption are 3 months or less in age.

Also, we can observe that each 12 months there is a considerable spike in occurences (n). This is likely because users will estimate age in years, and then convert to months (i.e. multiply by 12).

Initially, we believed the age variable would be very useful in a regression analysis, however now consider clustering should be explored.

3.2 Perform kmeans cluster analysis

We shall now perform kmeans analysis of the age data. Essentially, for a range of different cluster sizes we shall analysis how closely the data belongs to a particular group.

3.3 Apply kmeans clustering to dataset (k=4)

We observe that the optimal number of clusters (groups) is 4. Although the fit improves as the number of clusters incresaes above 4, this is only marginal.

The below table shows the mean number (in months) for each cluster. Each observation in the dataset will now have an Age_cluster assigned.

##        Age
## 1  2.49365
## 2 12.32121
## 3 33.66608
## 4 79.96130

3.4 Add name to cluster to provide meaning

We shall now apply a more understable name to the clusters, as per below.

3.5 Visualise observations (count) per cluster

We can see that puppy cluster has substantially more observations than the other clusters, this is consistent with early analysis of the age variable.

4.2 Correlation

The below correlation matrix shows the level of correlation between the variables. We can observe that the darker a colour (red or blue) the higher the correlation between the variables.

This will assist us in determining which variables to include as predictor variables in our models. It is important that predictor variables are independent therefore those with a strong correlation should not be included.

For example, we can observe a strong correlation between Vaccinated, Dewormed and Sterilized. We shall therefore only include one of these variables in our model.

7.8 Evaluation of regression model

By tuning the hyper-parameters in the model, we are able to select those with best performance (i.e. lowest error). Running the fitted model against the test data demonstrates a similar error rate, indicating the model is neither over or under fitted.

A possible application of this model would be conduct data entry checking by the rescuer (e.g. based on the other data provided, perhaps prompt the rescuer to check age if the variance is too great). However, the model has a relatively high variance so the suitability of this application will need to be fully tested.


Project Conclusion

Overall, we consider this to be a good dataset for analysis and model development. Predictive analysis can assist in a number of ways, for instance

  • help business to achieve better outcomes (more pets adopted);
  • share insights with PetFinder businesses in other countries; and
  • help to drive government policy in Malaysia (and internationally) to tackle issue of stray dogs and cats.

We were pleased with the results of our models, however we consider that other variables may be useful to explore. For instance, while we considered the number of photos we did not perform specific image analysis. Given the potential adopters will look at many potential pets, the quality of the photo may be an important variable.
